Hoodia gordonii [now discontinued]SASC on behalf of the regional Working Group on Indigenous Minorities. Legal representative supporting the SASC.SASC to receive 6 % of royalties from products; 8 % of income based on product development targets.Multiple patents relating to the use of Hoodia to control appetite, as well as for related products and processes,including its propagation.The BSA requires all forms of intellectual property developed and/or created by the CSIR and based on TK to be vested exclusively with the CSIR. The SASC has no right to claim any co-ownership. An economic partnershipOrganic certifications exist for many Hoodia products.There are no ethical trade certifications.Almost all cultivated on private lands.Over-harvesting in early years led to CITES Appendix II listing but no wider conservation measures exist.
Aspalathus linearis (rooibos)SASC and NKC.Ata late stage,representatives of "Cederberg Belt Indigenous Rooibos Farming Communities”were brought into negotiations but questions remain about representation and inclusion. Legal representative supporting the SASC. NGO Natural Justice supportingSASC and NKC receive 1.5 % of farm gate price of unprocessed rooibos,divided equally between the two councils.Over 150 patents relating to a range of applications for food supplements, medicinal and cosmetic applications.agreement between the European Union and South Africa, has led to the granting of geographic indication status for rooibos.In 1994, a trademark application for the name‘rooibos'was filed in the United States, but was contested by the rooibos industry and eventually cancelled.A range of organic and ethical trade certification standards, including the US National Organic Program (NOP), the Japanese Organic Standard (JAS),CERES and Ecocert.Multiple alternative trade organizations buy and sell Fairtrade rooibos from small-scale rooibos producers and rooibos-producing estates. Ethical tradeMostly cultivated on private farms with a limited amount of wild harvesting in communal or church- owned areas.Significant biodiversity impacts from the rooibos industry. BSA does not mention conservation.
